<H3> <TI>   Former Envoy Foresees No Accord on UN Seat </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Former Envoy Foresees No Accord on UN Seat </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1606130394 Tokyo KYODO in English 1256 GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1606130394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 16 KYODO -- The United Nations will not 
be able to revise its charter before 1996 to allow Japan to 
become a permanent member of its security council, former 
Japanese ambassador to the UN Yoshio Hatano predicted Thursday 
[16 June]. 
  Hatano also said in a speech that a midterm report on UN 
reform by a working committee, due this fall, will not detail an 
increase in the number of UN Security Council members. He said 
it would be impossible for the 184-nation working panel to 
produce an agreement. 

</TEXT>

