<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   SDPJ Official Opposes Support for Sanctions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    SDPJ Official Opposes Support for Sanctions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1706042694 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 17 
Jun 94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1706042694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From MAINICHI SHIMBUN 17 June Morning Edition] </F>
  [Text] Kozo Watanabe, head of the Social Democratic Party 
of Japan [SDPJ] delegation which has just returned from a visit 
to the DPRK (North Korea), held a news conference at the Japan 
National Press Club in Uchisaiwai-cho, Tokyo, on 16 June. With 
regard to the issue of North Korea's development of nuclear 
arms, Watanabe said, "This should still be resolved through 
dialogue; I am opposed to sanctions." The Japanese Government 
has informed the United States of its support of the draft UN 
Security Council resolution proposing five forms of sanctions, 
including arms embargo. His position directly contradicts 
government policy. 
  Watanabe further pointed out the need to: 1) ask Japan and 
other countries concerned to bring about an early reopening of 
talks between the United States and North Korea; 2) resume the 
Japan-DPRK normalization talks unconditionally; and 3) prepare 
for visits of North Korean VIP's to Japan to promote exchanges 
between various sectors of Japan and North Korea in order to 
create correct public opinion in Japan. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

