<DOCNO> FBIS4-29387 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas117__a94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-017-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  17 June 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Sanctions Resolution Appraised `Positively' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S. Sanctions Resolution Appraised `Positively' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1706031094 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 17 
Jun 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1706031094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN 17 June Morning Edition] </F>
  [Text] The government appraises positively the UN Security 
Council [UNSC] resolution on sanctions against the DPRK (North 
Korea) drafted by the United States because "it provides for a 
grace period to serve as a warning, and Japan's position has 
been taken into consideration to a certain extent," (according 
to a top Foreign Ministry official). If the resolution is 
adopted, Japan will promptly perform its duties as a UN member. 
  The government appreciates in particular the fact that the 
objective of the sanctions -- to make North Korea change its 
mind -- is clearly indicated. It believes that providing for a 
grace period of 30 days from the adoption of the resolution 
before sanctions are actually implemented is "a result of 
accommodating Japan's original proposal" on "step-by-step 
sanctions starting with a warning resolution," (according to a 
Foreign Ministry source). 
  Since the draft resolution is being considered at the UNSC, 
the focus is now on how China will react. The government says 
that "at this point, we have absolutely no indication how China 
will act," (according to a top Foreign Ministry official). It 
believes that although China's response may change the substance 
of the resolution, "it is improbable that the resolution will 
become any tougher." It would like to see the resolution passed 
in the end in a form conducive to encouraging North Korea to 
change its attitude through discussions in the UNSC involving 
China. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-29388 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas117__a94004" </HT>


