<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Okinawa Official on Yomitan Airfield Task Force </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Okinawa Official on Yomitan Airfield Task Force </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1706120894 Naha OKINAWA TIMES in Japanese 17 Jun 94 
Morning Edition p 2 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1706120894 </F>
<F P=104>  Naha OKINAWA TIMES </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] In connection with the task force on Yomitan 
Auxiliary Airfield, which the Japan-U.S. Joint Committee agreed 
to establish in a 16 June meeting, Masanori Yoshimoto, 
lieutenant governor of the Okinawa Prefectural Government, 
issued a comment. 
  In the comment, the lieutenant governor said the task force 
is mandated to make a technical study of how to secure an 
alternative cite for the current parachute drop training ground; 
the possibility of relocating Sobe Communications Station; and 
ways to handle various problems arising from the Yomitan 
Auxiliary Airfield. 
  In his comment, Lieutenant Governor Yoshimoto also said: The 
return of Yomitan Auxiliary Airfield is important for promoting 
the industry of Yomitan town and stabilizing the livelihood of 
residents there. The Okinawans have strongly demanded the 
return of the airfield. The Okinawa Prefectural Government 
intends to strongly ask both the Japanese and U.S. Governments 
to have the airfield returned in a visible way before 1995, when 
the 50th anniversary of the end of the Pacific War and battle 
for Okinawa is marked. 

</TEXT>

