<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on IAEA Reaction </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further on IAEA Reaction </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1706133994 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean 1301 GMT 17 
Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK1706133994 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["YONHAP from Vienna"] </F>
  [Text] The International Atomic Energy Agency [IAEA] has 
welcomed President Kim Il-song's promise to allow IAEA 
inspectors to stay in North Korea, but it has indicated that it 
is too early to assess if North Korea fulfills obligations of 
the Nuclear Safeguards Accord. 
  In an interview with an Austrian radio station today, IAEA 
spokesman David Kyd stressed that it is important to confirm if 
IAEA inspectors would have access to North Korea's seven 
declared nuclear facilities and that at present no details have 
been disclosed regarding it. He also said that details must be 
disclosed within a few days. 
  Regarding North Korea's announcement that it will observe 
obligations of the Nuclear Safeguards Accord, a Vienna-based 
diplomatic source said that such a proposal by North Korea 
cannot be a breakthrough in resolving the nuclear issue and 
stressed: To find a breakthrough, North Korea should announce 
that it would allow the IAEA team to inspect their seven 
declared facilities. Actually, the nuclear inspections should 
be carried out in North Korea. 

</TEXT>

