<F P=100> Brunei, Malaysia &amp; Singapore </F>
<F P=101> Malaysia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mahathir on Ties With Israel, Amendments </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Mahathir on Ties With Israel, Amendments </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK1906155594 Kuala Lumpur Radio Malaysia Network in English 
1300 GMT 19 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1906155594 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuala Lumpur Radio Malaysia Network </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Datuk Sri Dr. Mahathir says the enforcement of the 
unanimously approved amendments to the UMNO [United Malays 
National Organization] constitution to curb money politics will 
not be back dated. However, the prime minister said that UMNO 
members who resorted to money politics in the party election 
last year might lose their chances to be chosen as Barisan 
Nasional's candidates in the next general election. The 
amendments will be taken into account in deciding UMNO 
candidates to be fielded under the Barisan Nasional ticket at 
the general election. 
  He said this at the news conference at the end of the 
special 
UMNO general assembly in Kuala Lumpur. Datuk Sri Dr. Mahathir, 
who is UMNO president said that the date of the enforcement will 
not be back dated to ensure fairness to the members. However, 
proof for the use of money in the UMNO election last year would 
be taken into account to ensure that the party's candidates who 
were clean would represent the Barisan Nasional in the general 
election. 
  The prime minister also that Malaysia is not yet prepared to 
establish diplomatic relations with Israel because the 
government is not convinced that the peace process between 
Israel and the Palestinians is settled. 
  Replying to questions from newsmen at the end of the special 
sitting of UMNO general assembly this evening, the prime 
minister disclosed that he has so far received three letters 
from Yitzhaq Rabin. In his letters to Datuk Sri Dr. Mahathir, 
the Israeli prime minister has indicated his desire to establish 
diplomatic ties with Malaysia. 
  Datuk Sri Dr. Mahathir said he has replied to all three 
letters and has also informed the cabinet about the 
correspondence. When asked to comment on the report that a 
prominent Malaysian businessman had visited Jerusalem recently, 
the prime minister said he is not aware of the visit. He also 
said that there is at the moment no defined punishment for such 
wrong. The government has also taken action against the 
Malaysian reporter who covered the peace talks between Israel 
and the Palestinians recently. 

</TEXT>

