<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Summit Talks With ROK Scheduled for 2-3 Jul </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Summit Talks With ROK Scheduled for 2-3 Jul </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2006040094 Tokyo SANKEI SHIMBUN in Japanese 19 Jun 94 
Morning Edition p 1 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2006040094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo SANKEI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Katsuhiro Kuroda] </F>
  [Text] Seoul, 18 Jun -- On 18 June, a ROK Government 
source disclosed that Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata and President 
Kim Yong-sam are scheduled to hold Japan-ROK summit talks from 2 
to 3 July at Cheju Island, a resort in southern Korea. 
  This will be the first Japan-ROK summit talks since 
President 
Kim's visit to Japan last March. However, it will be the first 
such talks held in the ROK since the last talks were held in 
Kyongju between former Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa and 
President Kim Yong-sam last November. 
  Cheju Island has been designated as the site for talks 
because diplomatic authorities from the two countries expect 
that in promoting Japan-ROK summit diplomacy, it will be 
desirable to follow the Western style -- holding frequent 
meetings in an informal atmosphere. The last talks held in 
Japan were between [former Prime Minister] Kiichi Miyazawa and 
[former ROK President) No Tae-u in Kyoto, in November 1992. 
  The upcoming summit talks will be held over the weekend. 
With the Naples summit scheduled for 8 July, Japan intends to 
exchange views with the ROK on such issues as the North Korean 
nuclear program and the Korean peninsula situation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-29455 </DOCNO>
