<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-118-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  18 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   More Reports on Reaction to DPRK Related Issues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    More Reports on Reaction to DPRK Related Issues </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    U.S. Proposal for Talks With DPRK </H4>

<F P=102> OW1806141994 Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 18 Jun 94 
Morning Edition p 3 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1806141994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Following talks between former U.S. President 
Carter and North Korean President Kim Il-song, U.S. President 
Clinton said that the United States would resume talks with 
North Korea in connection the issue of North Korea's suspected 
development of nuclear arms. In response, the Japanese 
Government sees that "although it does not mean that the United 
States has decided to disregard North Korea's past development 
of nuclear weapons, the United States has lowered the hurdles of 
the conditions for settling the issue" (according to a Foreign 
Ministry source), thus analyzing that the U.S. Government has 
taken a stalwart and hard-bred position -- showing a flexible 
attitude while continuing to discuss sanctions. In this way the 
Japanese Government welcomes such a move toward resuming talks 
between the United States and North Korea. At the same time, 
however, the government is still wondering what Pyongyang is 
really thinking and believes talks would be tough, even if 
resumed. 
  An announcement by Assistant Undersecretary of State (for 
political and military affairs) Gallucci has drawn the attention 
of the Japanese Government. He stated "the United States pays 
attention to North Korea's readiness to return to the Nuclear 
Nonproliferation Treaty (NPT) and to fully meet the requirements 
of the International Atomic Energy Agency [IAEA] safeguards 
agreement, including special inspections." Judging from his 
statement, the government views that by using such a delicate 
expression as "pay attention," the United States, while easing 
conditions for resuming its talks with North Korea, has sent 
North Korea the message that "Clinton's statement does not mean 
disregarding the issue of North Korea's suspected development of 
nuclear weapons in the past." 
  Meanwhile, President Clinton's statement that "the United 
States would resume high-level talks with North Korea if 
Pyongyang is ready to freeze its nuclear program" has created a 
stir in Japan, causing the view that "the United States might 
ignore North Korea's development of nuclear weapons in the 
past." In this connection, speaking at a press conference, 
Chief Cabinet Secretary Hiroshi Kumagai said: "We do not think 
the United States only places emphasis on North Korea's future 
nuclear development." Meanwhile, a top Foreign Ministry leader 
said that "the U.S. Government statement does not mean it has 
changed its position," thus ruling out the U.S. Government's 
possible ignoring of North Korea's past nuclear development. 
Underlying these officials' remarks is the fact that "ignoring 
past nuclear development means that North Korea's nuclear threat 
to the safety of Japan could not be removed" (according to the 
Foreign Ministry source). It seems that the Japanese 
Government, in fact, has a slight concern about the U.S. 
statement because "there is a view within the U.S. Government 
that shelving the issue of North Korea's past nuclear 
development is inevitable" (according a Defense Agency source). 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-29456 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas118__a94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-118-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  19 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   More Reports on Reaction to DPRK Related Issues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    More Reports on Reaction to DPRK Related Issues </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    DPRK `Does Not Possess' Nuclear Arms </H4>

<F P=102> OW1906031794 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 19 
Jun 94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1906031794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN 19 Jun Morning Edition] </F>
  [Text] Speaking about the DPRK's (North Korea) suspected 
nuclear arms development program in a speech on a street in 
front of the southern gate of the Japan Railway Kinshi-cho 
Station on the evening of 18 June, Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata 
said, "I think North Korea does not possess them [nuclear arms], 
and I think it does not intend to produce them either." Thus 
for the first time, he expressed his belief that North Korea 
neither possesses nuclear arms nor has intentions to produce 
them. Also saying, "It may be that they do not want to appear 
intimidated into doing something," Hata suggested a view that 
the reason why North Korea is adamantly rejecting complete 
nuclear inspections by the International Atomic Energy Agency 
(IAEA) is because of pressure from the international community. 
  As for suspicions regarding North Korea's nuclear 
development, U.S. Defense Secretary Perry in a news conference 
recently said "it is possible that they have one or two nuclear 
weapons." The Japanese Government has also decided to discuss 
sanctions through the UN Security Council in cooperation with 
the United States, declaring "there is strong suspicion that 
North Korea is in the process of developing nuclear arms" 
(according to Foreign Ministry sources). The basis for the 
prime minister denying North Korea's possession of nuclear arms 
as well as its intent to develop them is not clear, but it is 
possible that his remark will have subtle impact on the 
direction of the system of Japan-U.S.-ROK cooperation and on 
future discussions of sanctions. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

