<H3> <TI>   More Reports on Reaction to DPRK Related Issues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    More Reports on Reaction to DPRK Related Issues </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Ruling Parties Work Out Policies </H4>

<F P=102> OW1706135594 Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN in Japanese 16 Jun 94 
Evening Edition p 1 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1706135594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] On 16 June, the ruling coalition worked out a draft 
plan on dealing with the DPRK's (North Korea) suspected nuclear 
arms development, which will be a focal point in discussion with 
both the Liberal Democratic Party [LDP] and the Social 
Democratic Party of Japan [SDPJ] on a possible future coalition 
framework. Among topics of the draft plan, which was formulated 
from the viewpoint of nonproliferation of nuclear weapons and 
Japan's security system, are: 1) Necessary domestic conditions 
will be created to enable Japan to respond to the United 
Nations' and the international community's decisions, including 
sanctions against North Korea; 2) Japan will closely cooperate 
with the United States and South Korea; and 3) the domestic 
crisis-control system, including legal measures, will be 
promptly established, and if necessary, the legislation of a 
"basic security law" will be considered. The coalition intends 
to submit the plan to both the LDP and the SDPJ early next week. 
  A policy study group, the "Committee To Discuss Japan's 
Security and Future," worked out the draft plan for the purpose 
of discussing it at policy consultations with the LDP and the 
SDPJ and preparing for future legislation by House of 
Representatives members. The committee (chaired by Yukihisa 
Yoshida, Democratic Socialist Party vice chairman) is comprised 
mainly of ruling coalition members. 
  With regard to concrete measures such as economic sanctions, 
the draft plan says Japan should cooperate not only in UN 
sanctions but also in "multilateral" actions such as those taken 
during the Gulf War. 
  As for cooperation with the United States and South Korea, 
it 
stipulates: "Japan will manage the Japan-U.S. security system 
flexibly depending on changes in the situation, and will provide 
support and cooperation to the United States within the 
framework of the system. On the other hand, Japan will 
positively promote cooperation with South Korea. To that end, 
legal and other arrangement will be made." 
  Regarding the establishment of the domestic crisis-control 
system, the draft plan points out: "An emphasis will be 
attached to national security; protection of Japanese people's 
lives, assets, and welfare; and maintenance of order in the 
Japanese society." It also notes the need to improve laws and 
regulations in anticipation of rescuing Japanese people living 
abroad and accepting refugees. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-29459 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas118__a94008" </HT>


