<H3> <TI>   Hata Reiterates Opposition to Nuclear Arms </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hata Reiterates Opposition to Nuclear Arms </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1806031794 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 18 
Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW1806031794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN 18 Jun Morning Edition] </F>
  [Text] Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata, asked at the House of 
Councillors' Budget Committee on 17 June if Japan has the 
capability or intention to develop nuclear arms, made a "cunning 
remark" that could be interpreted as having meant "Japan has the 
capability to develop nuclear arms." 
  Hiroshi Oki of the Liberal Democratic Party, discussing the 
Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty (NPT), said: "I think Japan has 
the capability to possess nuclear arms, but it has chosen not to 
possess them to cooperate (with the NPT). What do you think of 
this view, prime minister?" To that question, the prime 
minister replied, "I am completely of the same view." Later on, 
he told reporters in the Diet, "Certainly, Japan has the 
capability to possess nuclear arms, but has not produced them 
because of the Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty." 
  The government so far has totally denied the possibility of 
using nuclear power for military purposes, insisting that 
"Japan's use of nuclear power is limited to that for peaceful 
purposes." A person close to the prime minister admitted: "We 
cannot help if someone claimed his remarks deviated from what 
the government has said so far." As a result of the suspicions 
regarding the DPRK's (North Korea) nuclear development, there 
are now people in some circles in Asia and the United States 
"talking about Japan acquiring nuclear weapons." That being the 
case, the prime minister's office and the Ministry of Foreign 
Affairs are trying to dampen the excitement arising therefrom, 
saying, "The remarks can bring useless misunderstanding at home 
and abroad." 
  Chief Cabinet Secretary Hiroshi Kumagai, in a news 
conference 
on the evening of 17 June, revised the remarks of the prime 
minister, saying, "the prime minister's remarks were somewhat 
inadequate. Japan's nuclear power is limited to peaceful use." 
Frowning to the reporters, he said, "I must explain these 
things to the prime minister properly." 
  The prime minister looked as if he were surprised by such 
reaction within the government. Asked later in the evening by 
reporters to give his view again, he said, "Did I really say 
that? I do not remember." He then said emphatically, "What I am 
stressing is that although we have the capability, we are 
against nuclearization. I did not mean to say that we have the 
capability but do not use it. [sentence as received] We will 
never have nuclear weapons, from the standpoints of nuclear 
non-proliferation as well as from the three nonnuclear 
principles. There is no question about that." He thus in fact 
retracted his remarks, but this matter is likely to make waves, 
in a subtle manner, at home and abroad. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-29462 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas118__a94011" </HT>


