<H3> <TI>   Hata Briefed on OECD Council Meeting </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hata Briefed on OECD Council Meeting </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1706085594 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 17 
Jun 94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1706085594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN 16 Jun Evening Edition] </F>
  [Text] Nobuo Matsunaga and his party, who had represented 
Japan in the OECD Ministerial Council meeting, met with Prime 
Minister Tsutomu Hata at the Diet on the morning of 16 June, and 
reported to him on the discussions made at the council meeting. 
They reported that in a meeting with U.S. Secretary of State 
Warren Christopher and U.S. Trade Representative Mickey Kantor, 
both sides agreed that: 1) even though the Japan-U.S. economic 
framework talks have resumed, it will be impossible to resolve 
everything by the time of the industrial nations' summit (Naples 
summit) in July, and 2) the two countries must turn the 
Japan-U.S. top leaders' meeting at the Naples summit into a 
success by making progress in the framework talks, and it is 
necessary to make preparations for that. 
  In his report to Hata, Matsunaga said: "The United States 
has become realistic." The prime minister responded: "That is 
good." 
  In regards to the issue of the DPRK's (North Korea) 
suspected 
nuclear arms program, Matsunaga reported he told Secretary 
Christopher: "The ultimate target common to Japan and the 
United States is to have North Korea come to a table of dialogue 
and to have that country observe international rules. Our task 
is to make efforts toward peace." He also reported he told 
Christopher: "Japan will render its maximum possible 
cooperation, but if we have too high expectations on the 
effectiveness of sanctions, we can be disappointed." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

