<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Intraparty Group To Support Murayama </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Intraparty Group To Support Murayama </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1606135494 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 15 Jun 
94 Morning Edition p 2 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1606135494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] House of Representatives members of the Social 
Democratic Party of Japan [SDPJ], who support chairman Tomiichi 
Murayama, decided on 14 June to form a new intraparty group as a 
counterforce against the party's largest group "Democrats," 
which supports general secretary Wataru Kubo who is eager for 
SDPJ's return to the coalition administration. If the Tsutomu 
Hata cabinet refuses to resign en masse, the new group intends 
to strongly demand an early dissolution of the House of 
Representatives and a general election. Following the move, the 
conflict within the party will certainly worsen. 
  The new group will develop from the "group for promotion of 
true political reform," which backed Mr. Murayama in the 
chairmanship election in September last year. Former SDPJ 
General Secretary Tsuruo Yamaguchi (chairman of the House of 
Representatives' Budget Committee) proposed the formation of the 
new group. They will hold a general meeting on 21 June to 
formally form the group centering on Diet Administration 
Committee Chairman Koken Nosaka and Deputy General Secretary 
Hideyuki Maejima. They intend to expand and reorganize the 
group in the future by inviting middle-of-the-roaders and former 
cabinet members to join the group. 
  In a platform on "calling for regathering" which was worked 
out on 14 June, they agreed to the recent party policy of 
"demanding a dissolution [of the lower house] and a general 
election" if the Hata cabinet refuses to resign en masse. At 
the same time, the platform virtually stresses the need to start 
election preparations in anticipation of a lower house 
dissolution and a general election under the current multiseat 
electoral system, saying: "We have to prepare for establishing 
the structure for dealing with a general election." Moreover, 
it denies the possibility of allying with both Shinseito [Japan 
Renewal Party] and Komeito, saying: "We severely criticize the 
Liberal Democratic Party for its corrupted system resulting from 
money-oriented politics and the "Ichi-Ichi line" [the alliance 
between Shinseito Secretary General Ichiro Ozawa and Komeito 
Secretary General Yuichi Ichikawa] for their way of managing 
politics by use of pressure tactics. We need to put "social 
democrats and liberals" together as the third force." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-29473 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas118__a94022" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-118-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  15 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   SPDJ's Kubo Speaks on Political Realignment </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    SPDJ's Kubo Speaks on Political Realignment </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1706084994 Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN in Japanese 15 Jun 94 
Morning Edition p 2 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1706084994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Wataru Kubo, secretary general of the Social </F>
Democratic Party of Japan, by an unidentified YOMIURI SHIMBUN 
reporter; place and date not given] 
  [Text] [Reporter] The Social Democratic Party of Japan 
[SDPJ] has proposed that "the Hata Cabinet voluntarily resign en 
masse and a new coalition government be formed." Do you think 
that can happen? 
  [Kubo] It is important that the Hata administration 
completes its missions first. 
  [Reporter] How is your party planning to negotiate with the 
ruling parties concerning a new government? 
  [Kubo] It must be done very carefully. The negotiations 
cannot make headway if the SDPJ only adheres to its position and 
wants other parties to follow it. We will consolidate views 
within the party, but a consolidated view should be a flexible 
one to gain agreement on it from other parties that will 
participate (in the negotiations). 
  [Reporter] What are the conditions the SDPJ cannot accept at 
the negotiations? 
  [Kubo] As long as we are asking the Hata Cabinet to resign 
en masse, "Kaishin" (the parliamentary group) must be disbanded. 
We do not mind parties with the same ideas forming a floor 
group. But we think they should do so openly so that other 
floor groups can see what is going on. 
  [Reporter] What about the running of the government? 
  [Kubo] It should be run in a transparent and democratic way. 
As the final decision-making body, what we need is (not a 
representatives conference but) something like a general council 
comprised of 20-30 members, with the number of members 
apportioned by the size of the groups they represent. 
  [Reporter] Will your party submit a no-confidence motion 
against the cabinet? 
  [Kubo] This is not a question of having to choose whether 
the cabinet should resign to enable formation of a new 
government or the House of Representatives should be dissolved 
for a general election. If the Hata administration completes its 
missions and we can make headway in forming a new 
administration, there will be neither the dissolution of the 
House for a general election nor a no-confidence motion. But if 
this course of action is rejected, we will go for submission of 
the no-confidence motion. As long as we follow that step, I 
think the SDPJ can act in perfect union. 
  [Reporter] Some members of the ruling parties talk about a 
large scale cabinet reshuffle. What do you think about that? 
  [Kubo] There has been no specific proposal for it. Hence I 
think commenting on that at this point can be a barrier to 
possible new developments. But the cause that resulted in the 
SDPJ's departure from the coalition must be eliminated. 
  [Reporter] What do you think of a move on forming the 
so-called conservatives' alliance with conservatives? 
  [Kubo] This is something we must be most wary about. If a 
conservative coalition government is to come, it will be led by 
the Liberal Democratic Party [LDP], and this will mean reversing 
history. 
  [Reporter] Can the SDPJ participate in a government 
participated in by former Deputy Prime Minister Michio Watanabe 
of the LDP? 
  [Kubo] That will be difficult. If the ruling parties reject 
an alliance with the SDPJ, we should look for the possibility of 
forming a grand alliance between conservatives and reformists. 
  [Reporter] What is your view on a move toward an alliance 
between the LDP and the SDPJ? 
  [Kubo] I am opposed to the idea of allying with the LDP -- 
that idea that came in reaction to the thinking that "the SDPJ 
should not ally with Shinseito." That will only mean that the 
SDPJ will come to play a complementary role in the LDP 
administration. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-29474 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas118__a94023" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-118-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  20 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   SDPJ Confirms Outline of Coalition Blueprint </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    SDPJ Confirms Outline of Coalition Blueprint </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2006093094 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 20 
Jun 94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2006093094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN 20 June Morning Edition] </F>
  [Text] The Social Democratic Party of Japan [SDPJ] has 
basically confirmed the outline of its coalition blueprint which 
the party has been working out in preparation for policy 
consultations with the ruling coalition and other parties. 
Among the main pillars of the blueprint are: 1) The coalition 
should abide by agreements and memorandums signed at the time of 
the inauguration of former Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa's 
administration; 2) regarding policies, as a rule, the coalition 
should carry forward agreements reached at the time of the 
inauguration of Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata's administration, 
which includes the revision and abolition of the consumption 
tax; and 3) government affairs should be managed by a group of 
representatives from each party, and final decisions should be 
made via a meeting of party heads. 
  The party plans to finalize its blueprint after further 
integrating party members' opinions, but the party is divided 
over pending policy issues as well as which parties it plans to 
join in a new coalition alliance. It also places the mass 
resignation of the incumbent administration as a precondition to 
its forming a new coalition. Therefore, there is no question 
that rough sailing will be encountered regarding the SDPJ's 
finalizing its coalition blueprint and subsequent policy 
consultations with other parties. 
  In the blueprint, the SDPJ seeks to clarify what caused it 
to 
leave the coalition alliance as well as who is to be held 
responsible. However, the party does not intend to demand the 
resignation of those held responsible. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

