<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   LDP's Watanabe Interview on Political Situation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    LDP's Watanabe Interview on Political Situation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1606122294 Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN in Japanese 15 Jun 94 
Morning Edition p 2 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1606122294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Michio Watanabe, chairman of the Watanabe </F>
faction in the opposition Liberal Democratic Party, by an 
unidentified YOMIURI SHIMBUN reporter; place and date not given] 
  [Text] [YOMIURI SHIMBUN] The leadership of the opposition 
Liberal Democratic Party [LDP] plans to submit a no-confidence 
motion against the Hata cabinet to the Diet. What is your 
opinion? 
  [Watanabe] The LDP leadership will move in that direction. 
In 
case the House of Representatives is dissolved, the LDP could 
not fight in general elections without spending money. I think 
that no bank would lend 10 billion yen to the LDP. The LDP is 
prepared to fight in the general elections. At the present 
stage, I would like to refrain from commenting on the LDP's plan 
to submit a no- confidence motion against the Hata cabinet to 
the Diet. 
  [YOMIURI SHIMBUN] You are advocating plans to forge a 
conservative-conservative coalition. 
  [Watanabe] I intend to talk candidly with any politicians 
who 
share my political belief about how to run the state and handle 
the political situation. 
  [YOMIURI SHIMBUN] Do you think the ruling parties will 
propose to the opposition parties to hold talks to discuss how 
to form a new coalition government after the 1994 budget is 
passed in the Diet? 
  [Watanabe] There is a possibility of the ruling parties 
first 
holding talks with the opposition Social Democratic Party of 
Japan [SDPJ. If Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party], Komeito, and 
the Democratic Socialist Party believe that they will be able to 
break the present political deadlock and carry out their 
policies after forging an alliance with the SDPJ, then the SDPJ 
would return to the ruling coalition. If those ruling parties 
have no intention of forging the alliance with the SDPJ, the 
SDPJ will not return to the ruling coalition. 
  [YOMIURI SHIMBUN] Will the ruling parties approach the LDP 
for an alliance if they fail to forge an alliance with the SDPJ? 
  [Watanabe] Yes, they will approach the LDP. Their approach 
may trigger debates in the LDP and stir up the LDP. 
  [YOMIURI SHIMBUN] Ichiro Ozawa, secretary general of 
Shinseito, once said, "I am not sure whether we can reach a 
policy consensus with all members of the LDP." What do you think 
of his comment? 
  [Watanabe] If he thinks that the LDP is divided over 
policies, no alliance can be forged between the ruling parties 
and the LDP. A minority of LDP members share my political 
belief. If the LDP is unable to shape its own policy consensus, 
it will not be strange if the ruling parties seek an alliance 
with some LDP members who share their policies. 
  [YOMIURI SHIMBUN] If the Kono leadership rejects an offer 
from the ruling parties for policy consultations, how will you 
respond to the rejection? 
  [Watanabe] The LDP should hold intra-party discussion on the 
offer. 
  [YOMIURI SHIMBUN] Mr. Watanabe, will you quit the LDP? 
  [Watanabe] I will not break away from the LDP so lightly. I 
need not leave the LDP. 
  [YOMIURI SHIMBUN] Speaking on a television talk show, Mr. 
Ozawa has said, "If I am asked to apologize for what I have 
done, I will apologize." What is your comment? 
  [Watanabe] I take his statement as an indication of his 
eagerness to look for a way to break the current political 
deadlock and for a policy consensus after putting aside his 
personal feelings. 
  [YOMIURI SHIMBUN] Does the LDP have a blueprint for an 
LDP-SDPJ coalition? 
  [Watanabe] If there is no decision about who will become the 
prime minister and what the coalition will do, such a coalition 
would immediately collapse. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

