<H3> <TI>   Life Insurance Group Views Government Proposal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Life Insurance Group Views Government Proposal </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1706102294 Tokyo KYODO in English 1000 GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1706102294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 17 KYODO -- A top life insurance 
industry official Friday blasted a government report on postal 
insurance for proposing making postal life insurance more 
competitive with private-sector products. 
  Speaking in the capacity of chairman of the Life Insurance 
Association of japan, Toshiomi Uragami told reporters that the 
proposal runs counter to the law governing postal life insurance 
that limits services. 
  "This could help give more power to the bureaucracy," said 
Uragami, who is also president of Sumitomo Life Insurance Co. 
  The report, prepared by a study group for the Ministry of 
Posts and Telecommunications, says postal life insurance is 
serving to promote competition in the oligopolistic life 
insurance market. 
  Commenting also on a series of damage suits filed by 
variable 
life insurance policyholders against life insurance firms, 
Uragami said each life insurance company should have explained 
the feature of variable life insurance, and noted that the 
industry is reviewing a text on the subject for sales personnel. 
  Variable life insurance policies are investment-oriented 
policies that provide a return linked to an underlying portfolio 
of securities. 
  Variable life insurance was a big hit in the so-called 
bubble 
era in the late 1980s when a booming stock market held the 
promise of higher returns. 
  But with the stock market crumbling since, many 
policyholders 
facing huge losses have filed damages suits against life 
insurance firms. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

