<H3> <TI>   Prasong Reaffirms Adherence to UN Sanctions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Prasong Reaffirms Adherence to UN Sanctions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK1706051194 Bangkok BANGKOK POST in English 17 Jun 94 p 8 </F>
<F P=103> BK1706051194 </F>
<F P=104>  Bangkok BANGKOK POST </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Thailand yesterday said it would follow the UN 
decision on proposed sanctions against North Korea but made 
clear its preference for a negotiated solution to Pyongyang's 
refusal to allow nuclear inspections. 
  "Thailand will follow the United Nations resolution," 
Foreign 
Minister Prasong Sunsiri said. "But we hope that the situation 
will be resolved through negotiations." [passage omitted] 
  Foreign Minister Prasong confirmed that Thailand's 
ambassador 
to the UN in New York, Nit Phibunsongkhram, was in consultation 
with counterparts from other ASEAN states on the matter. 
  Thailand and ASEAN partners always follow the UN Security 
Council resolutions, a Bangkok-based Asian diplomat said. 
  But ASEAN member states "are not for the confrontational 
style of Western countries," the source added. 
  "Maybe we should give quiet diplomacy a chance. Methods of 
the West may not always be the best," the source said 
  Because of China's position, the UN Security Council is 
likely to find it more difficult than usual to forge a 
resolution on North Korea, the source added. 

</TEXT>

