<F P=100> Vietnam </F>
<H3> <TI>   Visits Hailed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Visits Hailed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK2006151794 Hanoi Voice of Vietnam in English 1000 GMT 20 
Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2006151794 </F>
<F P=104>  Hanoi Voice of Vietnam </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Vietnamese Prime Minister Vo Van Kiet has concluded 
his official visit to Ukraine, Kazakhstan, and Russia 
successfully. Following is our radio review on results of the 
visit. 
  Vietnam has traditional friendship and cooperation with 
Ukraine, Kazakhstan, Russia, and other republics of the former 
Soviet Union. After political changes that lead to the collapse 
of the former Soviet Union, relations between Vietnam and 
members of the former Soviet Union were suspended because these 
countries met with numerous difficulties. 
  The first visit to Ukraine, Kazakhstan, and Russia by the 
Vietnamese prime minister has breathed a new life into the 
traditional relations between Vietnam and these countries. 
  After the visit, the mutual understanding, friendship, and 
cooperation have been developed in the principles of equality 
and mutual benefit. It is worthy of note that during the visit, 
Vietnam and Russia signed four important agreements, including 
the treaty on the principle of friendly relations between the 
two countries. The treaty is a foundation for the restructuring 
of cooperation to make relations between the two countries 
develop effectively. 
  On this occasion, ministers, vice ministers, and businessmen 
who accompanied the prime minister exchanged views with their 
Russian counterparts to study the market and the possibility of 
cooperation between the two countries. 
  Following the visit, ministries, branches, and enterprises 
of 
Vietnam and Ukraine, Kazakhstan, and Russia will work out 
concrete plans for more effective cooperation. 
  Prime Minister Vo Van Kiet said upon his return home from 
Moscow that Vietnam has resumed its friendship with members of 
the Commonwealth of the Independent States on the basis of new 
relations. 

</TEXT>

