Daily Report 
<DATE1>  17 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Vietnam </F>
<H3> <TI>   UNHCR, Government Integration Program </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UNHCR, Government Integration Program </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK1806110494 Hanoi Voice of Vietnam in English 1000 GMT 17 
Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1806110494 </F>
<F P=104>  Hanoi Voice of Vietnam </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Following is the report on the conference to review 
the United Nations High Commission for Refugees' [UNHCR] five 
years of work on refugee program in Vietnam. 
  The conference to review the five years of work under the 
repatriation program for refugees were held on Friday and 
Saturday in Haiphong by the UNHCR and the Ministry of Labor, War 
Invalids, and Social Affairs. The conference was attended by 
the representatives of the interior, foreign and other 
ministries, representatives of 35 provinces and cities 
nationwide which have been involved in the program. 
  Over the past five years, the Vietnamese Government, with 
the 
assistance of UNHCR and international community, have received 
more than 62,000 voluntary repatriates, and helped them in 
bringing their lives back to normal and learning a trade to 
support themselves. Today, the UNHCR and the ECIP [EC 
Integration Program] have sponsored nearly 200 job training 
centers in Vietnam for returnees. Since June 1992, ECIP was 
expanded to 18 provinces and cities throughout the country with 
total expenditure set at $130 million. 
  Addressing the conference, UNHCR representative Mr. 
Christopher Carpenter highly valued the goodwill, humanitarian 
policy, and great effort made by the Vietnamese Government in 
helping returnees to settle down in their homeland. By the end 
of 1995, the UNHCR is prepared to receive more than 52,000 
Vietnamese voluntary repatriates still living in camps in 
foreign countries. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

