<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on North-South Summit Proposal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reportage on North-South Summit Proposal </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Seoul Notifies Allies, UN Council </H4>

<F P=102> SK2006055294 Seoul YONHAP in English 0542 GMT 20 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2006055294 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, June 20 (YONHAP) -- South Korea notified its 
allies and members of the U.N. Security Council Monday of its 
decision to propose a contact with North Korea for an 
inter-Korean summit. 
  Foreign Ministry spokesman Chang Ki-ho said the notices were 
sent to Japan, the United States, the permanent members of the 
Security Council and the International Atomic Energy Agency 
(IAEA) right after the morning's unification-related ministers' 
meeting decided in favor of the proposal. 
  Chang again welcomed the agreement on a South-North summit, 
saying that it moves forward inter-Korean relations in dealing 
with the nuclear problem. 
  "The significance lies in the fact that the South Korean 
Government will secure a role," said the spokesman. 
  He predicted that the talks leading up to the inter-Korean 
summit will progress in pace with the third round of high-level 
dialogue between Pyongyang and Washington, adding that North 
Korea's intentions must still be confirmed beforehand. 
  If it comes off, the summit will serve to revive the 
activities of various inter-Korean committees, including the 
joint Nuclear Control Commission to implement simultaneous 
nuclear inspections between the two sides. 
  "Inter-Korean dialogue will progress in a mutually 
complementary fashion with North Korea-U.S., North Korea-IAEA 
dialogue," Chang said. "South Korea and the United States will 
keep in close consultation." 

</TEXT>

