<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on North-South Summit Proposal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reportage on North-South Summit Proposal </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Issue `Meticulously Reviewed' </H4>

<F P=102> SK2006114294 Seoul YONHAP in English 1132 GMT 20 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2006114294 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, June 20 (YONHAP) -- President Kim Yong-sam 
said on Monday his government has in fact prepared for a 
South-North summit since long ago in expectation of a North 
Korean proposal for summit talks. 
  "This is why I readily accepted Kim Il-song's offer for a 
summit as conveyed by former U.S. President Jimmy Carter over 
the weekend," the president said. 
  President Kim made the remarks over a luncheon he hosted at 
Chongwadae [presidential offices] for a group of 97 bureau 
directors of non-economic government offices. 
  He said the South proposed to have a working-level meeting 
on 
Tuesday next week after the issue was meticulously reviewed over 
the weekend and Sunday morning. 
  "We offered to them to have a working-level meeting on June 
28 since we don't need to have complex talks and all we have to 
agree to is the place and time (of a summit)," Kim said. 
  He was quick to add, however, that the South cannot tolerate 
North Korea going nuclear. "There should be no nuclear arms on 
the Korean peninsula under any circumstances," the president 
stressed. 

</TEXT>

