<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kim Chong-il Declines Carter's Meeting Request </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kim Chong-il Declines Carter's Meeting Request </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1806104594 Seoul YONHAP in English 1017 GMT 18 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1806104594 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Carter-Kim Chong-il (replacement)" -- YONHAP headline] </F>
  [Text] Seoul, June 18 (YONHAP) -- North Korean leader Kim 
Il-song stressed the importance of high-level dialogue between 
Pyongyang and Washington, saying that is where the two sides 
could discuss ways to make North Korean nuclear program 
transparent, Former U.S. President Jimmy Carter told South 
Korean officials Saturday. 
  He delivered Kim's remarks in his talks with Foreign 
Minister 
Han Sung-chu after his arrival from Pyongyang, ministry 
spokesman Chang Ki-ho said. 
  Han was quoted as telling him that the North Korea-U.S. 
talks 
should be consulted between Seoul and Washington after the two 
countries confirm North Korea's true intentions. 
  Carter explained that reports about him telling Kim Il-song 
that the United States stopped discussing sanctions against 
North Korea was a result of misinterpretation, saying he meant 
the sanctions will be temporarily suspended on condition that 
the nuclear suspicion is resolved. 
  The ex-president and his wife returned to Seoul after a 
four-day visit to North Korea where he met twice with the senior 
Kim for extensive talks on the nuclear problem. 
  He came back with a message that Kim wants to directly meet 
South Korean President Kim Yong-sam "without any delay." 
  Meanwhile, Carter said he tried to meet also with Kim 
Il-song's heir-apparent son Kim Chong-il during his trip but was 
denied. 
  A South Korean official said Carter asked several times that 
he be able to meet junior Kim through North Korean officials but 
was refused, being told that Kim Chong-il did not have time. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

