<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   DPRK UN Envoy `Spurned' Gallucci's Remark </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    DPRK UN Envoy `Spurned' Gallucci's Remark </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1806011394 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean 0028 GMT 18 
Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK1806011394 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [YONHAP report from UN Headquarters] </F>
  [Text] On 17 June, James Rubin, a spokesman for the U.S. 
mission to the United Nations stated that consultations at the 
UN Security Council are proceeding without interruptions on the 
sanction resolution against North Korea. 
  Mr. Rubin was instructed by Madeline Albright, U.S. 
ambassador to the United Nations, to make this point clear. 
  This notwithstanding, Pak Kil-yon, North Korean ambassador 
to 
the United Nations, stated to reporters that the North Korean 
Government will not allow special inspections [tukbyol sachal] 
for two facilities suspected to be nuclear waste processing 
facilities. 
  On 16 June, U.S. Assistant Secretary of State Gallucci said: 
As a way to a general solution of the situation, North Korea 
expressed its willingness to completely accept safeguards 
regulations of the Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty and the 
International Atomic Energy Agency, including special 
inspections. 
  North Korean Ambassador Pak Kil-yon spurned Assistant 
Secretary of State Gallucci's remarks, stating that this was 
either Mr. Gallucci's personal interpretation or his personal 
pronouncement. 

</TEXT>

