<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   WPK Secretary Cited on `Challenge' to U.S. </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    WPK Secretary Cited on `Challenge' to U.S. </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1706151194 Tokyo KYODO in English 1456 GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1706151194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 17 KYODO -- A senior North Korean 
official told a visiting Japanese group in Pyongyang on Friday 
it is "impossible" for North Korea to challenge the U.S. nuclear 
arsenal, officials of the Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) said. 
The LDP officials said Hwang Chang-yop, a secretary of the 
(North) Korean Workers' Party [WPK], made the observation in a 
meeting with an LDP mission led by former Defense Agency chief 
Taku Yamasaki. 
  Hwang also reportedly told the LDP group that it is 
"meaningless" for his country to have nuclear weapons. He 
proposed an end to power diplomacy and warned that North Korea 
will retaliate if economic sanctions were imposed on Pyongyang, 
according to the LDP officials who talked with the Yamasaki 
group after the meeting in the North Korean capital. 
  Yamasaki explained Japan's commitment to the nuclear 
Nonproliferation Treaty and emphasized that a nuclear-free 
Korean peninsula is essential for peace and stability in North 
Asia, the LDP officials in Tokyo said. 

</TEXT>

