<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Results of Carter Trip to DPRK Welcomed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Results of Carter Trip to DPRK Welcomed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2006084494 Tokyo KYODO in English 0828 GMT 20 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2006084494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 20 KYODO -- Japan welcomed Monday 
recent developments toward solving the situation over North 
Korea's nuclear facilities, including possible resumption of 
talks between North korea and the United States and a summit 
between the top leaders of North and South Korea. 
  Japan welcomes the results of a visit to North Korea by 
former U.S. President Jimmy Carter, Vice Foreign Minister 
Kunihiko Saito said. 
  He told a press conference Japan will continue to watch the 
developments following Carter's Pyongyang trip and to make the 
utmost efforts in calling for a "serious" response from North 
Korea while maintaining close contact with the U.S. and South 
Korea. 
  Turning to Japan's proposal to assist North Korea to convert 
its present nuclear facilities to a light-water reactor, Saito 
echoed Foreign Minister Koji Kakizawa's remarks over the weekend 
that such aid would take place if Tokyo and Pyongyang discuss 
the issue within the context of normalization talks. 
  Since Japan's economic aid for North Korea after 
normaliztaion of bilateral relations is one of the topics in the 
normalization talks, it is natural that Japan's help to convert 
to a light-water reactor will also be discussed, Saito said. 
  Japan and North Korea have not held normalization talks 
since 
November 1992 due to a stalemate over international inspections 
of North Korea's nuclear facilities. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

