Daily Report 
<DATE1>  18 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tokyo Positive on DPRK-ROK Summit Agreement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tokyo Positive on DPRK-ROK Summit Agreement </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Summit Welcomed </H4>

<F P=102> OW1806140194 Tokyo KYODO in English 1349 GMT 18 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1806140194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 18 KYODO -- Japan greeted with cautious 
welcome a Saturday agreement between the top leaders of North 
and South Korea on a summit meeting to defuse the current crisis 
over Pyongyang's suspected nuclear arms program. 
  Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata said, "the fact that things have 
gone that far means a good climate has been produced. I hope 
the summit will succeed by all means." 
  Foreign Minister Koji Kakizawa also said he welcomed the 
news, and voiced expectations of moves toward North Korea's 
acceptance of international nuclear inspections. 
  A Foreign Ministry official concurred, saying, "that means 
the conditions are being set for a solution to the issue." 
  Earlier in the day, South Korean President Kim Yong-sam 
accepted North Korean President Kim Il-song's overture, agreeing 
to a summit meeting without conditions. 
  Some Japanese officials, however, hedged their welcome of 
the 
development with caution. 
  "We have seen similar moves before, but a solution has been 
prolonged," one ministry official said. 
  He said a real solution will not be found until North Korea 
fully accepts inspections by the International Atomic Energy 
Agency, the U.N. nuclear safety watchdog. 
  The official also pointed to the unofficial status of former 
President Jimmy Carter, who visited North Korea as a "private 
citizen" to seek a peaceful solution to the issue and conveyed 
the North Korean leader's proposal for a summit to Seoul. 
  He said Japan should keep close watch on Washington's 
official assessment on the results of Carter's mission. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

