<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sanctions Could Affect Imports From DPRK </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Sanctions Could Affect Imports From DPRK </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1706093394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0900 GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1706093394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 17 KYODO -- Proposed economic sanctions 
against North Korea could affect Japan's imports of men's 
clothing and food from that country, business sources said 
Friday [17 June]. 
  Japan has expressed support in principle for Washington's 
draft resolution to be submitted to the UN Security Council in 
response to North Korea's refusal to permit unhampered 
inspection of its nuclear facilities. 
  Aoyama Trading Co., a retailer of low-priced men's clothing, 
imports suits, blazers and other clothing from North Korea for 
exclusive marketing through its outlets nationwide, taking 
advantage of low labor costs in that country. Japan also 
imports mushrooms, crabs, shellfish and other food items from 
North Korea. 
  Customs-cleared imports of men's clothing from North Korea 
last year totaled about 9 billion yen, one-third of total 
Japanese imports from that country. Mushroom imports from North 
Korea last year, meanwhile, totaled 2.2 billion yen. 
  But an official of a major Japanese trading company, who 
asked to remain anonymous, said the sanctions would have only 
minimal effects on Japan's global trade. Japan-North Korea 
trade last year totaled 52.1 billion yen, only 0.1 percent of 
total Japanese trade. 

</TEXT>

