<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Nuclear Sub Port Calls Linked to Tension </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S. Nuclear Sub Port Calls Linked to Tension </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2006100494 Tokyo KYODO in English 0923 GMT 20 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2006100494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Nagasaki, June 20 KYODO -- The frequency of port 
calls in western Japan by U.S. nuclear-powered submarines has 
increased recently, apparently reflecting the tension over North 
Korea's suspected nuclear program, Maritime Self-Defense Force 
sources said Monday [20 June]. 
  The vessels may have approached North Korean coasts to 
investigate Pyongyang's military communications and various 
types of radio waves, the sources said. 
  Nuclear-powered attack submarines of the U.S. Navy made a 
record 17 calls last year at White Beach port in Japan's 
southernmost prefecture of Okinawa, according to local 
authorities. 
  Such U.S. Submarines called at sasebo port in nagasaki 
prefecture, southwestern Japan, 10 times in 1993, close to a 
record 11 calls the previous year, the authorities said. 
  Already this year, sasebo port has received visits by such 
submarines on nine occasions, they said. 
  Yokosuka port in kanagawa prefecture, eastern Japan, had 
received the largest number of calls by such vessels in the 
past, but saw only 15 visits last year, about half the annual 
figures of 1989 and 1991, they said. 
  Recently, many submarines have made port calls for only an 
hour or so on each visit, informed sources said, apparently to 
hand over data and fetch equipment needed for further 
information gathering. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

