<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   MITI Drafts Guidelines To Replace Cocom Rules </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    MITI Drafts Guidelines To Replace Cocom Rules </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2006103394 Tokyo KYODO in English 1000 GMT 20 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2006103394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 20 KYODO -- The Ministry of 
International Trade and Industry (MITI) said Monday [20 June] it 
has crafted a provisional legal framework on export controls for 
strategically-sensitive products. 
  The move follows the international scrapping of Coordinating 
Committee for Multilateral Export Control (Cocom) rules in March. 
  The Western-bloc Cocom was set up in 1949 to prevent the 
transfer of military technology to communist countries but was 
disbanded in line with the demise of the communist bloc. 
  Revisions to part of the foreign exchange control ordinance 
and the export trade control ordinance will be in effect until 
Japan and the 22 other former Cocom members work out a new 
international framework for checking exports of 
strategically-sensitive products around October, MITI said. 
  The revisions will be approved by the cabinet Tuesday and to 
be enforced on July, the ministry said. 
  Under the provisional rules, some of the former Cocom items 
regarded as especially strategically sensitive, will be subject 
to export controls for all destinations other than the 23 
countries, MITI said. 
  Among such items are cipher equipment and components for 
unmanned submarines, it said. 
  Other former Cocom-designated products will be subject to 
export controls for the "watch-list" countries of Iran, Iraq, 
Libya and North Korea. 
  Export monitoring, less strict than controls, will be 
applied 
to exports of many former Cocom items to all nations except the 
23 former Cocom members and the four watch-list countries. 
  There are no Japanese export items that are immediately 
affected by the new provisional rules, a MITI official said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

