<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hata Said To Resign if No-Confidence Vote Passes </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hata Said To Resign if No-Confidence Vote Passes </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1806135594 Tokyo KYODO in English 1340 GMT 18 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1806135594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 18 KYODO -- Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata 
said Saturday he will opt for stepping down if a no-confidence 
vote passes the Diet, ruling out a snap poll under the current 
election system which is to be replaced soon. 
  "If a no-confidence vote passes (the House of 
Representatives), I will have to dissolve the lower house or 
resign. But I have been saying the dissolution should not be 
done," Hata said in a speech in front of a Tokyo railway station. 
  "That would leave me with (the only choice of) resigning en 
masse. In that case, I would have to obtain the understanding 
of the people and of the opposition parties," he said. 
  The largest opposition Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) has 
pledged to submit a motion of no-confidence against Hata's 
minority cabinet after the budget bills pass the Diet, expected 
next week. 
  If the Social Democratic Party (SDP), the second largest 
opposition party, supports the LDP's move, it will clinch the 
no- confidence vote, leaving Hata with the choice of either 
dissolving the lower house and calling snap general elections or 
stepping down with his ministers. 
  Hata has been insisting the next general elections should be 
held under a new election system of single constituencies 
combined with proportional representation in line with the 
political reform bills that passed the Diet in January. A 
government panel is currently redrawing the electoral map for 
the new system. 
  Ironically, Saturday marked the first anniversary of the 
Diet's passage of a no-confidence vote against then Prime 
Minister Kiichi Miyazawa, which led to the demise of the LDP's 
38-year rule, and paved the way for a broad coalition led by 
former Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa. 
  Miyazawa lost his grip on power due to voting by Hata and 
other LDP pro-political reform lawmakers who supported the 
opposition- proposed no-confidence motion. 
  Hata left the LDP along with Ichiro Ozawa, now a top 
coalition strategist, and their followers to create Shinseito 
[Japan Renewal Party], a key component of the coalition. 
  Hata, in recalling the day one year ago, said the move 
triggered drastic change in Japan's political landscape. 
  "I voted for the motion while saying in my mind 'please 
forgive me' because I thought I had to open up (a new era) in 
Japan's politics," he said. "I am recollecting the day with a 
heart filled with emotion." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-29598 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas118_a_94029" </HT>


