<H3> <TI>   Ozawa: No Need for Hosokawa To Testify at Diet </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ozawa: No Need for Hosokawa To Testify at Diet </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1706122894 Tokyo KYODO in English 1041 GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1706122894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 17 KYODO -- Ichiro Ozawa, top 
strategist of the coalition government, said Friday [17 June] 
former Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa does not have to testify 
about his suspected shady financial deals at the Diet. 
  Ozawa called "invalid" the House of Representatives Budget 
Committee's decision Thursday to summon Hosokawa next Tuesday. 
  Ozawa, secretary general of Shinseito, the coalition's core 
party led by Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata, met reporters and 
criticized the decision in which Budget Committee Chairman 
Tsuruo Yamaguchi overrode the ruling coalition's objections and 
declared his panel would make Hosokawa testify under oath. 
  The opposition parties forced a motion through the lower 
house budget panel to summon Hosokawa in an apparent bid to use 
Hosokawa's plight to their advantage and force Hata's minority 
government to step down. 
  Hosokawa's questionable deals were partly responsible for 
his 
April 8 announcement of his resignation as prime minister. 
  Hosokawa's former financial secretary appeared before the 
budget panel Wednesday to say Hosokawa has indeed paid back a 
loan of 100 million yen borrowed in 1982 from the 
scandal-tainted Sagawa Kyubin trucking firm. 
  The secretary, Masatoshi Miyama, denied allegations that 
Hosokawa may not have paid back the 100 million yen loan and 
that it was received as a secret political donation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

