<H3> <TI>   Doi Rejects Call for Questioning Hosokawa </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Doi Rejects Call for Questioning Hosokawa </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2006094494 Tokyo KYODO in English 0914 GMT 20 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2006094494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 20 KYODO -- House of Representatives 
Speaker Takako Doi on Monday [20 June] rejected a plea from 
former Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa to nullify a 
parliamentary decision to summon him as a sworn witness over his 
alleged financial irregularities, officials said. 
  In a meeting with Masuo Matsuoka, secretary general of 
Hosokawa's Japan New Party (JNP), Doi reportedly said that the 
lower house "cannot and will not annul (the decision to summon 
him) as it has already issued a summons." 
  After the meeting, Matsuoka told reporters that it is not 
yet 
decided whether Hosokawa will appear before Tuesday's budget 
committee session. 
  Hosokawa, in a letter to the speaker, had asked the lower 
house to review the parliamentary procedures that led to his 
summoning. 
  At a session of the budget committee on Thursday, its 
chairman, Tsuruo Yamaguchi, declared that his panel unanimously 
approved a proposal to summon the former prime minister. 
  Some parties in the ruling coalition of Prime Minister 
Tsutomu Hata lodged a protest against the procedure, saying the 
committee's decision contravened a longtime parliamentary 
practice of authorizing such summons only when all parties 
approved of such a proposal. 
  Budget committee members from the JNP and two other 
coalition 
parties, Komeito [Clean Government Party] and Shinseito [Japan 
Renewal Party], declared at Thursday's session their opposition 
to the proposal to summon Hosokawa. 

</TEXT>

