<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Takemura on Early Realignment of Parties </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Takemura on Early Realignment of Parties </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2006060194 Tokyo KYODO in English 0527 GMT 20 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2006060194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 20 KYODO -- Former Chief Cabinet 
Secretary Masayoshi Takemura on Monday [20 June] expressed hope 
that a reconfiguration of political parties will be achieved, as 
quickly as possible, to put an end to the current political 
disarray in Japan. 
  "I don't think it is good for the political community to 
continue shaking," Takemura said in a lecture hosted by KYODO 
NEWS SERVICE. "I want to find a specific course for political 
realignment at an early date." 
  Takemura, who heads new party Sakigake [Harbinger], also 
voiced his hope that the primary opposition Liberal Democratic 
Party (LDP) will split, in response to its internal differences 
over key policies and political beliefs, and merge with other 
political parties. 
  Saying the once-dominant LDP's historical role is over, 
Takemura predicted the anticipated political realignment will 
engulf the LDP and the Social Democratic Party (SDP) [Social 
Democratic Party of Japan (SDPJ]), the second largest opposition 
force. 
  The leader of the 15-member new party Sakigake described the 
rule by the current minority coalition government of Prime 
Minister Tsutomu Hata as an "abnormal situation" and spoke of 
the need to form a stable majority administration in one way or 
another. 
  The SDP, the largest contingent of the government of former 
Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa, quit the ruling coalition in 
April, leaving Hata overseeing Japan's first minority government 
since 1955. 
  New party Sakigake, an LDP breakaway and also a member of 
the 
previous administration, fled the governing alliance because of 
differences with its coalition partners over political 
strategies. 

</TEXT>

