<H3> <TI>   Nakasone on Conservative, Centrist Parties Ties </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Nakasone on Conservative, Centrist Parties Ties </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1706073294 Tokyo KYODO in English 0333 GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1706073294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Washington, June 17 Kyodo -- Former Japanese Prime 
Minister Yasuhiro Nakasone on Thursday advocated a wide alliance 
among conservative, liberal and centrist forces to create a 
stable ruling coalition. 
  Nakasone, who is on a tour of the United States, told 
reporters that such an alliance would best suit the current 
political situation. 
  ``If the Social Democratic Party (SDP) is like that, policy 
(alliance) among new conservatives, liberals, and, if necessary, 
centrist forces, may be appropriate,'' he said, referring to the 
second-largest opposition SDP's departure from the ruling 
coalition in April that left the first minority government in 
decades. 
  His remarks were viewed by observers as an indication of 
acceptance of a coalition with centrist forces such as Komeito 
and the Democratic Socialist Party (DSP) -- and even with some 
SDP right-wingers. 
  Nakasone, a kingpin of the largest opposition Liberal 
Democratic Party (LDP), is known as a staunch conservative and 
has been leery of leftist socialists. 
  It is well known that Nakasone is seeking a coalition 
between 
the LDP and its splinter party Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party], 
headed by Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata, as envisaged by Shinseito 
strategist Ichiro Ozawa and the LDP's Michio Watanabe, a former 
foreign minister. 
  But his latest remarks appear to show he is tilting toward a 
coalition which includes some liberal and centrist forces for at 
least the current period of transition, according to observers. 
  Nakasone also said that political realignment will progress 
in the coming months in line with the political stance of the 
parties. 

</TEXT>

