<H3> <TI>   SDPJ To Present Coalition Plan to Ruling Camp, LDP </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    SDPJ To Present Coalition Plan to Ruling Camp, LDP </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1706053694 Tokyo KYODO in English 0515 GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1706053694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 17 KYODO -- A senior Social Democratic 
Party (SDP) [of Japan, SDPJ] official said on Friday [17 June] 
the party will present an alliance-seeking initiative to both 
the ruling coalition and the Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) for 
negotiations to create a new governing coalition. 
  Koken Nosaka, who heads the Diet Administration Committee of 
the second-largest opposition party, told a press conference 
that the party will compile an alliance proposal by next 
Wednesday to present to the ruling coalition and the largest 
opposition party. 
  "We want to play a leading role in creating a stable 
government," Nosaka said. 
  Nosaka was skeptical about the possibility of Prime Minister 
Tsutomu Hata heading the new coalition government after he 
resigns, as required by SDP's prerequisite for alliance talks. 
  "It is unthinkable" that the premier who resigns will 
immediately assume the same post again, he said. 
  Meanwhile, SDP Chairman Tomiichi Murayama made a renewed 
call 
for Hata, who heads the first minority government in four 
decades, to step down to set the stage for coalition talks with 
the SDP. 
  At a meeting with SDP-supporting labor unions, Murayama also 
said the SDP will submit a motion of no-confidence against the 
Hata cabinet if he takes a stance that it cannot agree with. 
  The SDP withdrew from the coalition in late April after the 
abrupt formation of a parliamentary group excluding the party. 
  LDP President Yohei Kono made clear the party still plans to 
seek a no-confidence vote against Hata. 
  Kono said at a meeting of party executives that the Hata 
administration has not obtained a sufficient mandate from the 
people and that it has also lost international credibility over 
the failure in the Japan-U.S. trade talks. 
  Kono also pointed to Hata's lukewarm posture toward the 
lingering corruption charges against former Prime Minister 
Morihiro Hosokawa as a reason to seek a no-confidence vote. 
  Management and Coordination Agency Director General Koshiro 
Ishada, who heads Komeito, a major coalition component, said the 
SDP's move Thursday to join forces with the LDP at the House of 
Representatives Budget Committee to decide to summon Hosokawa to 
testify before the Diet over the financial dealings is bound to 
have some impact on the political situation. 
  But Health and Welfare Minister Keigo Ouchi, former head of 
the Democratic Socialist Party, another coalition member, said 
so far the SDP's alliance with the LDP is limited to the 
Hosokawa issue, and said it is not yet clear whether or not the 
SDP will fully cooperate with the LDP in seeking a no-confidence 
vote. 

</TEXT>

