  [Text] Tokyo, June 20 KYODO -- The head of the Social 
Democratic Party (SDP) [of Japan, SDPJ] said Monday [20 June] 
the second largest opposition party will join forces with the 
main opposition Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) to form a stopgap 
government in the event the SDP's coalition talks with the 
present minority government break down. 
  Tomiichi Murayama made the comment at a meeting of former 
SDP 
lawmakers at a time when the fragile coalition led by Prime 
Minister Tsutomu Hata is preparing to hold talks with the SDP to 
lure it back into the fold. 
  The SDP chairman told the meeting the proposed alliance with 
the LDP would be temporary, limited to governing until House of 
Representatives general elections which may follow a threatened 
no-confidence motion by the LDP against the Hata government. 
The SDP has indicated it may support a no-confidence vote. 
  The SDP left the governing alliance in April after the 
establishment of a new parliamentary group by some coalition 
parties, excluding the SDP. 

