<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reports on U.S.-Japan Trade Talks Continue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reports on U.S.-Japan Trade Talks Continue </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    `Progress Was Made' in Telecom Talks </H4>

<F P=102> OW1906064894 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 18 Jun 
94 Morning Edition p 5 -- FOR OFFICIAl USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1906064894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] On 17 June, Japanese and U.S. negotiators concluded 
two days of talks in Tokyo regarding government procurement of 
telecommunications equipment in the Japan-U.S. framework trade 
talks. The negotiators held discussions on improvements in 
bidding procedures, which the Japanese Government compiled last 
spring, and on benchmarks (objective criteria) to gauge the 
openness of Japanese markets to foreign access. Apparently, 
"progress was made" (as stated by a Japanese negotiating 
official) in the talks. However, U.S. negotiators reiterated 
that they wanted to hold discussions regarding the procurement 
of telecommunications equipment by the Nippon Telegraph and 
Telephone Corporation (NTT), something which Japan has rejected. 
As a result, the negotiators were unable to narrow the gap 
between their opposing views. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

