<F P=100> Cambodia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage Continues on Roundtable Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reportage Continues on Roundtable Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Outcome of Meeting </H4>

<F P=102> BK1806072594 Phnom Penh National Radio of Cambodia Network 
in Cambodian 1300 GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1806072594 </F>
<F P=104>  Phnom Penh National Radio of Cambodia Network 
in Cambodian 1300 GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=105> Cambodian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [17 June press communique of the Royal Government </F>
spokesman's office -- read by announcer] 
  [Text] In pursuance of the august idea of His Majesty King 
Norodom Sihanpouk Varaman of the Kingdom of Cambodia [KOC], a 
KOC delegation took part in the roundtable commission's meeting 
with the representative of the Khmer Rouge held at the Damnak 
Chan pavilion of the royal palace, Phnom Penh, on 15 and 16 June 
1994 under the chairmanship of Samdech Chakkrei Nhoek Chulong, 
high representative of the king, and in the presence of the 
samdech supreme patriarch and Samdech Mohakhousananda. 
  This roundtable commission's meeting was a continuation of 
the roundtable meeting held at the Chhanghsu-on royal residence 
on 27 and 28 May 1994 in line with the fourth provision of the 
joint communique issued by this roundtable meeting which 
proceeded under the august chairmanship of His Majesty King 
Norodom Sihanouk Varaman, the venerated king of the Cambodian 
nation. 
  The presence of the KOC delegation at this latest meeting 
was 
further irrefutable proof to show that the National Assembly and 
the Royal Government, the legal institutions born out of the 
elections and the constitution, had the goodwill and most 
unshakable determination to find a peaceful solution to the 
remaining Cambodian problems with the aim of bringing peace for 
the people, because this peace constitutes the key factor for 
bringing about happiness and development in the nation in 
conformity with the august desire of the venerated king. 
  During this discussion, we once again voiced our solemn 
support for the agenda of the meeting graciously set by His 
Majesty the king on 5 June 1994: namely, 1) an unconditional, 
immediate, and permanent cease-fire in all of the territory of 
the KOC; and 2) the minimal policy program, which was a proposal 
of the Khmer Rouge. 
  The KOC delegation agreed to this cease-fire with a high 
sense of responsibility. At the same time, the delegation also 
proposed that the cease-fire should begin on 30 June 1994, at 
noon, or in the early morning of 30 June 1994. However, it was 
most regrettable that the august initiative raised by His 
Majesty the king in pleading for an unconditional, immediate, 
and permanent cease-fire in all of the territory of the KOC -- a 
most necessary and urgent requirement for the Cambodian nation 
and people -- was made conditional by the Khmer Rouge, who 
wanted to reject it once again despite the earnest pleas made by 
the samdech supreme patriarch and Samdech Mohakhousananda for 
them to accept this cease-fire. The Khmer Rouge continued to 
raise the same unreasonable and unrealistic arguments and 
demanded that the participants of the meeting divert their 
attention to discussing their proposal instead, which in reality 
was an excuse for the Khmer Rouge to carry on their "fighting 
while negotiating" strategy to prolong the war. 
  As a matter of fact, besides refusing to agree to a 
cease-fire schedule, the Khmer Rouge also ambiguously talked 
about the composition of a cease-fire supervision commission, 
using it as a condition to set the cease-fire schedule, which is 
completely contrary to the august idea of His Majesty the king 
concerning an unconditional, immediate cease-fire. 
  Moreover, the Khmer Rouge also raised the issue of a 
competent technical commission to supervise the cease-fire 
without by any means trying to specifically describe this 
commission. 
  Through this meeting with the Khmer Rouge, it could be seen 
even more clearly that the Khmer Rouge have no desire whatsoever 
to find a solution for ending the remaining Cambodian problems 
through peaceful means. The impasse resulting from the 
categorical inflexibility of the Khmer Rouge caused the 
roundtable commission's meeting to conclude on 16 June 1994, at 
noon, without any specific and positive results that could be 
used as a basis for us to agree on for the holding of further 
meetings and talks with the Khmer Rouge. This will be in line 
with the idea of His Majesty the king, who had warned before the 
meeting that he would not initiate any more roundtable meetings. 
  Phnom Penh, 17 June 1994 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

