<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Radio Reports Carter's News Conference in Panmunjom </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Radio Reports Carter's News Conference in Panmunjom </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1806132294 Pyongyang Korean Central Broadcasting Network 
in Korean 1216 GMT 18 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK1806132294 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang Korean Central Broadcasting Network 
in Korean 1216 GMT 18 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=105> Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Former U.S. President Jimmy Carter has held a news 
conference with domestic and foreign reporters in Panmunjom 
after visiting our country. 
  In the news conference he talked about the sincere effort 
that will be made [songuiinun noryokul kiuryo nagalte taehaeso 
marhaessupnida] for the future harmony [hwamok] between the DPRK 
and the United States, thus expressing his deep gratitude to 
President Kim Il-song for his hospitality given to him, as well 
as to his entourage. He said that his talks with President Kim 
Il-song had proceeded in an openhearted [hosimtanhoe] atmosphere. 
  Commenting on his impressions of a visit to our country, he 
said that he was very greatly moved by the art performance by 
students and children. Also, he said that the art performance 
that he watched was an outstanding performance that can never be 
forgotten in his whole life, and that he hopes that the whole 
world will be able to watch the Korean children's performance. 
  Regarding the nuclear issue and DPRK-U.S. relations, he said 
that direct talks between the DPRK and the United States will be 
resumed in the future, and that North Korea's graphite-moderated 
reactor will be converted into a light-water reactor. Also, he 
expressed the conviction that all problems regarding the nuclear 
issue would be solved smoothly. 
  Regarding the reunification of Korea, he stressed that this 
issue is the issue that should be resolved by the Korean people 
in the North and South themselves. 
  Regarding the issue of sanctions against our country, he 
said 
that the issue to take sanction steps is a very serious mistake 
[chejae chochilul chwihalttae taehan munjenun maeu simgakhan 
oryurago hamyonso], and that the sanctions will not have an 
effective influence. 
  He said he expects that the United States will no longer 
pursue the sanctions against Korea. 

</TEXT>

