<H3> <TI>   KCNA Reports Carter News Conference </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    KCNA Reports Carter News Conference </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1806161794 Pyongyang KCNA in English 1736 GMT 18 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1806161794 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, June 18 (KCNA) -- Former U.S. President 
Jimmy Carter called a press conference at the Thongil House [as 
received] in the north side portion of Panmunjom today before 
leaving the DPRK. 
  He arrived in Pyongyang on June 15. 
  He told local and foreign reporters that his trip to the 
Democratic People's Republic of Korea was positive. He said, 
"All my discussions with President Kim Il-song were very open, 
frank and without restraint and I think the result is positive." 
  He added that direct talks between the DPRK and the United 
States can be resumed. 
  He said North Korea's graphite moderated reactor system will 
be replaced by a light water reactor system. 
  "Overall questions about nuclear weapons can be resolved," 
he 
said. 
  He said he thinks "sanctions" are definitely a serious 
mistake. "If the things continue to go well there is no need to 
consider sanctions any more." 
  "I have never thought sanctions are effective or necessary," 
he said. "Hope now my government will agree that the crisis is 
over and the sanctions are no more necessary for consideration." 
[sentence as received] 
  Giving his impressions of Korea, he said the most exciting 
impression was made when he witnessed the performance of 
children in Pyongyang yesterday. "This was the most remarkable 
performance I have seen in my life," he added. 
  "Hope the whole world will see the children of North Korea 
as 
we appreciated yesterday," he said. [sentence as received] 
  He said he will strive with sincerity for harmony between 
the 
two countries. 

</TEXT>

