<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Agreement' on Trade Before G-7 Summit Difficult </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Agreement' on Trade Before G-7 Summit Difficult </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1906112894 Tokyo KYODO in English 1119 GMT 19 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1906112894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Oita, June 19 KYODO -- International Trade and 
Industry Minister Eijiro Hata said Sunday it will be difficult 
for Japan and the United States to reach "a complete agreement" 
in their framework trade talks by the G-7 summit meeting 
scheduled for July 8-10 in Naples. 
  At a press meeting in Oita, western Japan, Hata did not 
elaborate further, but said the two countries have already 
agreed on the direction of the trade talks. Hata also said that 
Japan would not agree to setting "numerical targets" since it 
could lead to managed trade. Japan has strongly refused U.S. 
demands to set numerical targets to measure progress in the 
opening of the Japanese market. Hata added that Japan will not 
replace "objective criteria" with numerical targests. 
  Both Japanese and U.S. officials have said they want to get 
an agreement at least on some industry sectors prior to the 
Naples summit of the Group of Seven leading industrialized 
nations. A bilateral summit meeting between Prime Minister 
Tsutomu Hata and U.S. President Bill Clinton is scheduled in 
Naples. 
  The current trade talks between Japan and the U.S. focus on 
seven Japanese market sectors of particular interest to U.S. 
firms. Among them are Japanese Government procurement of 
telecommunications and medical equipment, insurance, and 
automobiles and auto parts. 
  The two countries have also kicked off negotiations to ease 
market-access regulations in Japan's financial sector, tighten 
the protection of foreign patents and copyrights in Japan and 
increase sales of foreign-made flat glass in Japan. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-29638 </DOCNO>
