<H3> <TI>   Australian Deputy Prime Minsiter Visits Tokyo </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Australian Deputy Prime Minsiter Visits Tokyo </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Meets Kakizawa </H4>

<F P=102> OW2006040294 Tokyo KYODO in English 0325 GMT 20 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2006040294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 20 KYODO -- Australian Deputy Prime 
Minister Brian Howe called on Japan on Monday [20 June] to 
participate in an international conference this year to discuss 
problems of cities in the Asia-Pacific region, Foreign Ministry 
officials said. 
  Howe, also minister for housing and regional development, 
made the call in a 20-minute meeting with Japanese Foreign 
Minister Koji Kakizawa. 
  Giving high marks to Japan's contributions in the 
Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD), 
Howe said he hopes Japan would participate in the "International 
Conference on Cities and New Global Economies," to be co-hosted 
by Australia and the OECD in Melbourne in November. 
  He also expressed hope that Australia and Japan could 
cooperate at another international conference on social 
development scheduled for next March in Denmark, they said. 
  Kakizawa told Howe he is interested in problems concerning 
housing and city development and said Japan would like to take 
part in the conference, according to the officials. 
  Kakizawa said he hopes Japan and Australia could continue to 
cooperate in the Asia-Pacific region and coordinate aid policies 
for the South Pacific islands. 
  He also voiced hope that summit meetings of the leaders of 
the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) forum will continue 
to be held in the future, they said. 
  An informal summit of APEC leaders was held in Seattle last 
November and another summit is to be held this year in Indonesia. 
  Howe arrived in Japan last Friday to hold talks with 
Japanese 
Government officials on regional development and ask for Japan's 
participation in the conference. 
  He is to meet Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata later Monday. 

</TEXT>

