Daily Report 
<DATE1>  14 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> SOUTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Burma </F>
<H3> <TI>   Editorial Hails Than Shwe Visit to Laos </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Editorial Hails Than Shwe Visit to Laos </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK2006143194 Rangoon THE NEW LIGHT OF BURMA in English 14 
Jun 94 p 4 </F>

<F P=103> BK2006143194 </F>
<F P=104>  Rangoon THE NEW LIGHT OF BURMA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Editorial: "Mutual Understanding Enhanced"] </F>
  [Text] The five-day official friendly visit of State Law 
and Order Restoration Council [SLORC] Chairman Senior General 
[Than Shwe] and delegation to the Lao People's Democratic 
Republic [LPDR] at the invitation of the President of the LPDR, 
His Excellency Nouhak Phoumsavan, must be hailed as highly 
successful and has helped enhance mutual understanding. What is 
significant is that the two leaders and the two leaderships were 
able to have a cordial exchange of views which bespeak the 
longstanding cordial relations which have existed between the 
leaders and peoples of our two nations. 
  Sr. Gen. Than Shwe and President Nouhak Phoumsavan had a 
friendly and fruitful discussion on bilateral and international 
matters of common interest in a cordial atmosphere. In the same 
spirit, the high-level officials of the two friendly nations 
were able to hold discussions on matters of common interest and 
sign agreements of related matters. 
  The fruitful talks led to the signing of the following 
agreements: 
  1. Agreement between the Government of the Union of Myanmar 
[Burma] and the Government of the LPDR on the fixed 
International Boundary between the two countries in the Mekong 
River. 
  2. Agreement on the establishment of a Joint Commission for 
Bilateral Cooperation between the Government of the Union of 
Myanmar and the Government of the LPDR. 
  3. Agreement on Tourism Cooperation between the Government 
of the Union of Myanmar and the Government of the LPDR. 
  Moreover, the senior general, Madame Than Shwe, and the 
delegation were able to absorb the historical and cultural 
aspects of Lao life which are common to both sides, for we had 
to suffer unfortunate circumstances although we are both 
independent sovereign nations. The grace and charm of the Lao 
artistes who performed traditional dances for the benefit of the 
guests also reflect similarities between the cultures of our two 
nations. 
  We share much of the Buddhist heritage and the senior 
general 
and Madame Than Shwe as well as members of the entourage were 
able to visit pagodas and pay obeisance to the senior Lao sangha 
[Buddhist monk], present offertories and share merits. 
  It is heartening to summarize that the two sides were able 
to 
highly evaluate the success of the state visit which serves as 
firm basis for the enhancement of the friendly and 
good-neighborly relations and cooperation between the two 
countries in the future, thus contributing to the promotion of 
peace, stability, and cooperation for the development of the 
region. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

