<H3> <TI>   Japan Urged To Hasten Technology Transfer </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Japan Urged To Hasten Technology Transfer </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK2006103294 Kuala Lumpur BERNAMA in English 0655 GMT 20 Jun 
94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2006103294 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuala Lumpur BERNAMA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Kuala Lumpur, June 20 (OANA/BERNAMA) -- Japanese 
investors must speed up the process of transferring technology 
or face the risk of losing their market share in Malaysia, 
Minister of Science, Technology and Environment, Law Hieng Ding, 
said Monday. 
  He said that if they did not transfer the technology, they 
would lose their market niche to European countries and the 
United States, not only in Malaysia but in the region too. 
  The Japanese, however, now realise the negative consequences 
of not transferring technology and are moving fast towards this 
goal, he told reporters after launching the Finger-Lock System 
of Polytron Resources Sdn Bhd [Private Limited] here. 
  The security system uses finger print instead of a key or a 
card to gain access into a building or home. 
  Law said the rapid development in the Asia-Pacific would 
entail Japan to change its policy in respect of technology 
transfer. 

</TEXT>

