<F P=100> Brunei, Malaysia &amp; Singapore </F>
<F P=101> Malaysia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fundamentalists Urged To Abandon Movement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Fundamentalists Urged To Abandon Movement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK2006163294 Kuala Lumpur NEW SUNDAY TIMES in English 19 Jun 
94 p 2 </F>

<F P=103> BK2006163294 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuala Lumpur NEW SUNDAY TIMES </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Rembau, Sat. -- Negeri Sembilan Menteri Besar 
[State Chief Minister] Tan Sri Mohamed Isa Abdul Samad has urged 
Al-Arqam followers to abandon the movement which has not only 
deviated from Islamic teachings but is also a threat to national 
security. 
  He said the state government viewed the movement's deviant 
activities seriously and would intensify efforts to explain to 
the people about the group. 
  "We do not want to see the racial harmony enjoyed by the 
people under the Barisan Nasional government threatened by the 
movement," he said in response to Prime Minister Datuk Sri Dr. 
Mahathir Mohamed's statement that the Al-Arqam movement had 
reached a level that may threaten national security. 
  Speaking after attending a district-level Maal Hijrah 
[Hegira 
Muslim new year] celebration here yesterday, he said the state 
government would support any Federal Government action to curb 
the movement's activities. 
  He said religious officers and mosque administrators in all 
districts would be asked to explain in detail to their 
congregation on where the movement went wrong. 
  "In this way we will be able to check the movement's 
deviationist activities from spreading," he said, adding that 
the state government had banned the movement last year. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

