<F P=100> Brunei, Malaysia &amp; Singapore </F>
<F P=101> Malaysia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Finance Minister Notes Economic Growth </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Finance Minister Notes Economic Growth </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK1806101594 Kuala Lumpur Voice of Malaysia in English 0600 
GMT 18 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1806101594 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuala Lumpur Voice of Malaysia </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Malaysian economy grew at a robust 8.6 percent 
in the first quarter of this year against 7.6 percent for the 
same period in 1993. Deputy Prime Minister and Finance Minister 
Datuk Sri Anwar Ibrahim said the stronger growth was driven by 
firmer export growth and higher domestic demand, particularly 
investment. He said this in Kuala Lumpur last night. He also 
said that inflation remains stable at 4.3 percent during the 
first four months of the year, similar to the rate recorded in 
the same period of 1993. The government is confident that 
inflation will be kept at about four percent this year compared 
with a month-to-month basis. 
  He added that the consumer price index, which measures the 
rate of inflation, had in fact dropped marginally. Datuk Sri 
Anwar said the manufacturing sector, which expanded by 13.7 
percent, led the first quarter gross domestic product growth 
followed by the construction sector with a 12 percent expansion, 
services 9.6 percent, and agriculture 2.2 percent. 
  Speaking in Serdang today, Datuk Sri Anwar said the 
government has never neglected rural development and its record 
in striking a balance between the interest of the rural and 
urban community is the best in the region. He said the 
contention of the country's development programs were not 
comprehensive was mere empty talk which the opposition indulged 
in because they refused to acknowledge the government's 
achievements. He said the government's development (?democracy) 
was to develop the people in all aspects of life to ensure no 
one was left behind. 
  The deputy prime minister said not many countries have 
achieved a high rate of development and none can match 
Malaysia's record in rural development. 

</TEXT>

