<F P=100> Brunei, Malaysia &amp; Singapore </F>
<F P=101> Singapore </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Ong Confirms Resumption of Duties </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    President Ong Confirms Resumption of Duties </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK1906094094 Singapore THE STRAITS TIMES in English 18 Jun 
94 p 3 </F>

<F P=103> BK1906094094 </F>
<F P=104>  Singapore THE STRAITS TIMES </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] President Ong Teng Cheong said last night he has 
recovered fully from the loss of his voice and has resumed 
normal duties since Monday. 
  Speaking to reporters during the intermission of the Beijing 
People's Art Theatre performance at the Victoria Theatre, he 
said the loss of his voice last week was due to a virus 
infection. 
  He had been warded at the National University Hospital on 
June 8 for rest and observation after a routine medical 
check-up, which included an endoscopy of his stomach, colon, and 
rectum and was discharged last Saturday. 
  He said that he developed a sore throat after the endoscopy 
procedure during which a tube-like instrument was lowered into 
his body. 
  "I think I probably have some slight trauma to the throat 
after the procedure, but the loss of voice was due to a virus 
infection which occurred unfortunately at about the same time of 
the endoscopy," he said. 
  He described the infection as a "coincidence, a rare 
coincidence." 
  He said that since he was diagnosed as suffering fron 
low-grade lymphoma in l992 he has been going for regular 
check-ups. 
  He has blood tests every two to three months and other tests 
such as computed tomography scans and X-rays once or twice a 
year. 
  He added that when his lymphoma was first diagnosed, his 
doctors had not recommended treatment "but to wait and watch" 
for signs of progression of the disease. 
  So far, they had not recommended any treatment. 
  "I lead a normal life, I don't suffer from pain, so 
everything is normal," he said. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

