<F P=100> Cambodia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cabinet Approves Investment Bill </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Cabinet Approves Investment Bill </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK2106062994 Phnom Penh National Radio of Cambodia Network 
in Cambodian 1200 GMT 20 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2106062994 </F>
<F P=104>  Phnom Penh National Radio of Cambodia Network 
in Cambodian 1200 GMT 20 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=105> Cambodian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Press communique of the Royal Government spokesman"; dated </F>
20 June -- read by announcer] 
  [Text] A plenary session of the cabinet was held at 1500 
on the afternoon of 18 June under the chairmanship of Prince 
Krompreah Norodom Ranariddh and Samdech Hun Sen, first and 
second prime ministers of the Kingdom of Cambodia [KoC] to 
examine the immigration bill. After a thorough debate, the 
cabinet approved this investment bill which has eight chapters 
and 26 articles. 
  The cabinet commended the experts for skillfully drafting 
the 
bill which has contents suitable for the urgent requirements of 
the nation and domestic and foreign investment. 
  The cabinet paid attention to discussing and improving the 
draft to attract investments to the KoC, thus creating and 
increasing jobs for the people and enhancing the production in 
the following domains: 
  I. Concerning Chapter II dealing with the Cambodian 
Development Council [CDC], the cabinet unanimously regarded the 
CDC as the general staff of the Royal Government of Cambodia 
[RGC] in investment work and the competent body which has sole 
access to the issuance of investment permits. At the same time, 
the cabinet agreed on the protection of investors' rights and 
freedoms. The arrangement, function, and composition of the CDC 
will be set by a sub-decree. 
  II. Concerning Chapter III dealing with the investment 
guarantees, the RGC recognizes all investors equally, that is, 
there will be no discrimination based on their nationality and 
race. The RGC guarantees that it will not nationalize the 
assets of the investors, ensures that it will not [words 
indistinct]. 
  III. Concerning Chapter IV dealing with the incentives for 
investment, the priority domains to be encouraged are as follows: 
  1. Modern or high-technology industries. 
  2. Labor-intensive investment projects (?including) tourism, 
industry, and agriculture. 
  3. Projects to enhance the export or production of 
import-substitutes, agro-industrial projects, and [words 
indistinct]. 
  4. Projects to develop the provinces and the countryside, 
infrastructure [words indistinct] located in special development 
zones. 
  Tax and profit incentives are as follows: 
  A nine-prcent tax on income; the exemption of tax on profits 
up to eight years depending on the characteristics of each 
investment project, whose order of priority will be determined 
by the RGC in a sub-decree; tax exemption on all reinvested 
profits; 100-percent tax exemption on goods that are exported; 
100-percent tax exemption on the import of goods to serve 
investments (?and) projects producing 80 percent of their goods 
for export [words indistinct] tourism industry, labor-intensive 
industries [words indistinct]; and permits for the import of 
foreign supervisors, specialists, technicians, and specialized 
workers, and their partners in line with the KoC's immigration 
law. 
  IV. Concerning Chapter V dealing with the ownership and use 
of land. In keeping with the Constitution, the problem of land 
ownership [words indistinct]. This means that the Cambodian 
partner must own over 50 percent of the total investment. 
  Foreign individuals or partners are allowed to use land 
through a long-term lease of up to 70 years. The use of land 
[words indistinct]. 
  V. Also on that occasion, the cabinet agreed that any 
individual dispute shall be reconciled first by the CDC before 
being forwarded to court. Also, any dispute with the 
authorities concerned will be sent to (?the Cambodian Investment 
Board). 
  The implementation of this investment law [words 
indistinct]. 
However, this law will not affect investors who have been 
operating before this law comes into effect. 
  The cabinet ended its session at (?2000) in an atmosphere of 
unity and with high sense of responsibility. 
  [Dated] Phnom Penh, 20 June 1994 

</TEXT>

