<F P=100> Indonesia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ranariddh, Hun Sen Visit Indonesia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ranariddh, Hun Sen Visit Indonesia </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Murdiono Comments </H4>

<F P=102> BK2106100794 Jakarta Radio Republik Indonesia Network in 
Indonesian 0700 GMT 21 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2106100794 </F>
<F P=104>  Jakarta Radio Republik Indonesia Network </F>
<F P=105>  Indonesian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Murdiono, minister/state secretary, briefed 
reporters on the outcome of talks between President Suharto and 
Cambodian co-Prime Ministers Prince Norodom Ranariddh and Hun 
Sen at the Merdeka [Presidential] Palace in Jakarta today. 
  He said that the Government of Cambodia has expressed its 
wish for the essential goods from Indonesia to be dispatched 
directly to Phnom Penh instead of going through a third country. 
In the past, Indonesian goods exported to Cambodia were 
delivered through a third country. The leaders had also reached 
an agreement on the banking and trade procedures to be observed 
by the two countries. 
  Murdiono said that Indonesia is still in great demand for 
the 
supply of soybeans to fulfill its domestic needs. For this, 
President Suharto suggested that if Cambodia could produce the 
commodity, bilateral trade between the two countries could be 
stepped up. 
  Meanwhile, speaking at a news conference at Wisma Negara 
[State Guest House] today, Prince Norodom Ranariddh said that 
Cambodia will not seek military assistance from Indonesia but 
wants to learn more about Indonesian military's experience in 
handling the communist and separatist movements. 
  According to Hun Sen, the only problem that Cambodia faces 
now is its internal politics, because the Khmer Rouge group 
still wants to remain isolated. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

